shared_text:
Chris Matheson
September 8 at 3:48 PM ·

Education is a tough gig even during the best of times, yet alone in the midst of a global pandemic. Under normal circumstances educational leaders are tasked with meeting the needs and expectations of multiple stakeholders while keeping the safety and education of children first and foremost in their thinking and decision making. This is complicated as emotions run hot, tension is high, and stress abounds as we all navigate a global pandemic and social upheaval here in the United States.

This week I sent our school leaders a brief video asking them to commit to three actions for the 2020-2021 academic year. In all honesty, I most likely could have developed a list of 1000 actions for the…

link:
Do you often find yourself worrying in things you cannot control? Here are some helpful tips:
1. Determine what you can control
2. Focus on your influence
3. Identify your fears
4. Differentiate between ruminating and problem-solving
5. Create a plan to manage stress
6. Develop healthy affirmations
——
Do you have any tips for letting go of things you cannot control? Let us know!

We are excited to have Dr. Sara Wine back in the Fishbowl for today's episode. Dr. Wine is the founder of Wine Holistic Health Center located in Brighton, MI. Wine Holistic Health Center's Mission is to "Get to the root cause of your health and set you on a path of wellness." We are extremely grateful that Dr. Wine was willing to take time out of her busy schedule to share with us her thoughts and concerns surrounding the current state of affairs. In addition, she shares some great times surrounding educator self-care during this mandated shutdown. She also shares some tips on how educators can prepare to serve students when we return to school. Lastly, she shares some wisdom for parents to help their children navigate their time at home.

Congratulations to three of the NexTech High School students in Lansing that were recognized and awarded scholarships last week!

NexTech High School of Lansing
March 16, 2018 at 12:48 PM ·

At last night's Scholarship Dinner for the Wilson Talent Center (WTC), Nextech seniors Bailey Griffith, Ben Williams, and Caleb Wood were awarded scholarships from local donors. The delicious food was prepared and served by WTC's Culinary Arts students, including Ben Williams. It was a wonderful celebration of some outstanding students. Nextech is proud to say that 3 of our seniors earned 5 out of the 22 scholarships awarded last night. Congratulations Bailey, Ben, and Caleb!
